<h3>Pre-Header</h3>
<p>The pre-header is the thin strip that sits above the main header, often used for quick-access details.</p>

<h3>Favicon</h3>
<p>A favicon is the small icon that appears in a browser tab next to your website title.</p>

<h3>Navigation</h3>
<p>The navigation is the set of links at the top of a website that helps visitors find what theyâ€™re looking for.</p>

<h3>Breadcrumbs</h3>
<p>Breadcrumbs show visitors their location within a websiteâ€™s hierarchy, e.g. <em>Home > Blog > Post</em>.</p>

<h3>Website Content</h3>
<p>Content includes text, images, videos, audio, and all elements designed to inform, engage, or persuade your audience.</p>

<h3>Homepage</h3>
<p>The homepage is the front page of a site â€” the central hub to guide visitors.</p>

<h3>Homepage Hero Area</h3>
<p>The top section of a homepage with a headline, sub-headline, CTA, and visual element to grab attention.</p>

<h3>Slider</h3>
<p>A rotating series of images, often on the homepage. Once popular, now less common due to performance issues.</p>

<h3>Alt Text</h3>
<p>Alt text describes images for accessibility and SEO.</p>

<h3>Sidebar</h3>
<p>A sidebar is a vertical column beside main content, often with ads, links, or a search box.</p>

<h3>Sub-Footer</h3>
<p>A section above the footer with secondary navigation, contact info, or social icons.</p>

<h3>Footer</h3>
<p>The footer is the final section of a webpage, with legal, policy, and contact details.</p>

<h3>Landing Page</h3>
<p>A landing page is built for a single focused action, often without distractions like headers or footers.</p>

<h3>Call To Action (CTA)</h3>
<p>A CTA is a request for visitors to take action, e.g., click a button or sign up.</p>

<h3>Above the Fold</h3>
<p>The part of a webpage visible without scrolling. Important CTAs are often placed here.</p>

<h3>Blog</h3>
<p>A blog displays posts in chronological order, usually conversational in tone.</p>

<h3>Card Design</h3>
<p>Card design organizes content into distinct tiles in a grid layout, popular for galleries or blog pages.</p>

<h2>Additional Terminology Of Modern Websites</h2>

<h3>WordPress</h3>
<p>WordPress is a CMS (content management system) that powers millions of websites using themes and plugins.</p>

<h3>Hosting</h3>
<p>Hosting is the server space where your website lives, provided by companies like HostGator or BlueHost.</p>

<h3>Caching</h3>
<p>Caching stores a temporary version of a website to make it load faster.</p>

<h3>Domain Name (URL)</h3>
<p>A domain name is your websiteâ€™s address, e.g., <em>markbrinker.com</em>.</p>

<h3>Domain Registrar</h3>
<p>A domain registrar is where you purchase and register your domain name, e.g., NameCheap or GoDaddy.</p>

<h3>301 Redirect</h3>
<p>A 301 redirect permanently forwards visitors from one URL to another, preserving SEO value.</p>

<h3>404 Error Page</h3>
